Climate-econ code

I have coded the climate-econ model, basing it on the economic model we have been using. This means it differs slightly from the model used by Bovari et al. in their 2018 papers (“Coping”" and “Debt and Damages”).

# Packages
library("deSolve")
library("RColorBrewer")
colourful <- brewer.pal(n = 3, name = "Set1")

# Set-up
source('Code/June_2020/model_w_climate/pars.R')     # load parameters
source('Code/June_2020/model_w_climate/funcs.R')    # load functions
source('Code/June_2020/model_w_climate/sim.R')      # load simulation file
#==============================================================================
# ### Set initial conditions
lambda_init <-0.9
omega_init <-  0.9
debt_share_init <-0.2

IC <- c(
  K       =  lambda_init * Parms[['nu']],
  w       =  omega_init,
  p       =  1,
  debt    = debt_share_init * lambda_init,
  a       = 1,
  pop     = 1,
  g_sigma =  -0.0105,  # Growth rate of the emissions intensity of the economy
  n       =  0.03,     # Emissions reduction rate
  E_ind   =  35.85,    # Industrial CO2-e emissions, in Gt CO2-e
  CO2_AT  =  851,      # CO2-e concentration in the atmosphere layer, in Gt C
  CO2_UP  =  460,      # CO2-e concentration in the biosphere and upper ocean layer, in Gt C
  CO2_LO  =  1740,     # CO2-e concentration in the deep ocean layer, in Gt C
  E_land  =  2.6,      # Exogenous land use change CO2-e emissions, in Gt CO2-e
  p_BS    =  547.22,   # Backstop technology price level
  Temp    =  0.85,     # Temperature in the atmosphere, biosphere, and upper ocean layer, in degrees Celsius
  Temp_LO =  0.0068    # Temperature in the deep ocean layer, in degrees Celsius
)


#=================================================================================
# Set up simulation
Time <- c(
  start         =     2020, 
  end           =     2120,
  step          =     0.05
)

Options <- list(
  invest = 'exp',  # exp / arctan / lin
  damage_scenario = 'None',
  p_carb_scheme = 'Low',
  subsidy = 0   # fraction of abatement costs subsidized by government
)

I run it without a carbon price or subsidy or climate damages, and it performs as teh previous code did:

Good initial conditions

IC[['n']] = 0
Parms[['carbon_slope']] = 0

Sim <- simulation(time       = Time,
                        init_state = IC,
                        parms      = Parms,
                        method     = 'rk4')

Bad initial conditions

lambda_init <-0.6
omega_init <- 0.7
debt_share_init <- 1.5
IC[['K']] = lambda_init * Parms[['nu']]
IC[['w']] = omega_init
IC[['debt']] = debt_share_init * lambda_init


Sim <- simulation(time       = Time,
                        init_state = IC,
                        parms      = Parms,
                        method     = 'rk4')

Pricing differences

The AFD code has slightly different pricing dynamics. However, we can convert between what they used and what we are using.

AFD inflation: \[i = \eta^*(\xi^* (\omega + \iota)-1)\] \[= \eta^* \xi^* \omega + \eta^* \xi^* \iota - \eta^* \xi^* \] \[= \eta(\xi\omega -1 )\]

where \(\eta = \eta^* - \eta^* \xi^* \iota\) and \(\xi = \frac{\xi^*}{1-\xi^* \iota}\). The AFD code also implies \(\gamma=0\).

AFD parameters:

eta.AFD     <- 0.3       
markup.AFD  <- 1.2           
omitted.AFD <- 0.3

eta <- eta.AFD - eta.AFD * markup.AFD * omitted.AFD 
print(eta)
## [1] 0.192
markup <- markup.AFD / (1 - markup.AFD * omitted.AFD)
print(markup)
## [1] 1.875

Basin search

What happens if the AFD pricing parameters are used with the basin search code? It was previously observed that a higher markup rate \(\xi\) increased the basin of attraction to the ‘good’ equilibrium.

I ran the basin search code with \(\eta = 0.192\), \(\xi=1.875\), and \(\gamma=0\).

source('Code/May_2020/compare_models/basin_search.R')
result <- compute.basin.3d(n_pts=10,  eta=0.192, markup = 1.875, gamma=0, type="sobol")

Thoughts

  • my climate-econ code always crashes with significant carbon pricing. Should I adjust pricing parameters so this doesn’t happen (if possible)?
  • which pricing parameters to use?
  • how to implement carbon pricing? Right now it is linear, but it should probably be capped.
